onnect/coronavirus-information-center Novel Coronavirus Information Center] by [[Elsevier]]\n* [https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus COVID-19 Resource Centre] by [[The Lancet]]\n* [https://www.springernature.com/gp/researchers/campaigns/coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19] by [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n* [https://www.nejm.org/coronavirus Coronavirus (Covid-19)] by [[New England Journal of Medicine]]\n* [https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/ Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus] by [[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley Publishing]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|short=true}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:2010s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in China]]\n[[Category:2019 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2019 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:21st-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Atypical pneumonias]]\n[[Category:Current events]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in China]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Wuhan]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Pandemics]]\n[[Category:Pandemics with high degree of misinformation]]\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern]]\n", "name_user": "EllenCT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCases:section wikilinks for new terms below", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "City Palace, Potsdam", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = Potsdam City Palace\n| native_name          = Potsdamer Stadtschloss\n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      = \n| image                = Potsdam Stadtschloss 07-2017.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Main facade of the Potsdam City Palace in 2017\n| map_type             = Germany\n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = Location in Germany\n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = [[Palace]]\n| architectural_style  = [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]], [[Rococo]]\n| structural_system    = \n| cost                 =  \n| client               = [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg]]<br>[[Frederick II of Prussia]] <br> State of Brandenburg\n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| location             = \n| address              = \n| location_town        = [[Potsdam]]\n| location_country     = [[Germany]]\n| coordinates          = {{coord|52.394|13.060|display=inline}}\n| start_date           = 1662\n| completion_date      = 1669\n| inauguration_date    = \n| renovation_date      = 1744\u201352, 2006\u201313 (rebuilt)\n| height               = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] \n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| awards               =\n| url                  = \n| references           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Potsdam City Palace''' ({{lang-de|Potsdamer Stadtschloss}}) is a building in [[Potsdam]], [[Germany]], located on the [[Old Market Square, Potsdam | Old Market Square]], next to the [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]] (''Nikolaikirche''). It was the second [[official residence]] (the winter residence) of the [[Rulers of Brandenburg|margraves and electors of Brandenburg]], later [[King in Prussia|kings in Prussia]], [[List of rulers of Prussia|kings of Prussia]] and [[List of German monarchs|German emperors]]. \n\nHeavily damaged in [[World War II]] and later dismantled by the [[East Germany | East German]] communist regime, the partial reconstruction, with historic facades and a modern interior, was completed in late 2013. The building has since served to house the [[Landtag of Brandenburg|parliament of the federal state of Brandenburg]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] palace was constructed on the site of an earlier fortification from 1662 to 1669 under [[Prince-Elector]] [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Friedrich Wilhelm]], and was rebuilt from 1744 to 1752 by [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] under [[Frederick II of Prussia|Friedrich II]], who performed additional interior decoration. It stood as one of the most important examples of [[Frederician Rococo]].\n\nDuring an Allied bombing attack on 14 April 1945 the City Palace was bombed and burned out, although 83 per cent of the building structure survived.<ref name=\"dw.com\">{{Cite web|title = In Surprise Vote, Potsdam Decides to Rebuild Baroque Palace {{!}} Culture {{!}} DW.COM {{!}} 05.01.2007|url = http://www.dw.com/en/in-surprise-vote-potsdam-decides-to-rebuild-baroque-palace/a-2301379|website = DW.COM|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>  However, the ruling communist party (official name: [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany]], SED) demolished the ruin in 1960 for ideological reasons.{{citation needed|reason=What ideological reasons?|date=June 2016}} The formerly cohesive Old Market lost its face. The only portion of the palace left standing was the stables, which today houses the Potsdam Museum of Film.\n\nIn 1991 construction of a modern theatre, which had been initially planned under the GDR, began on the site of the City Palace. However, the project stalled. Although some steel framework was erected, it was subsequently torn down.\n\n==Reconstruction==\nAfter the fall of the Berlin Wall, the ruling Left Party (the successor to the communists) twice rejected initiatives to reconstruct the Palace. However, in 1996 strong encouragement was provided by the \"Potsdam Project\" run by the Summer Academy for Young Architects of the [[Prince of Wales]]'s London Institute of Architecture.<ref name=\"Landtag\">\"Brief history of the new Landtag building: The long road from city palace to Landtag palace\", Landtag Brandenburg, 2014. http://www.landtag.brandenburg.de/media_fast/5701/Schriftenreihe_1_2014_englisch.pdf</ref> The Project recommended reinstatement of the historical footprint of the Palace via a partial reconstruction.<ref>''The Potsdam project, 1996'', HRH The Prince of Wales, Charles; Hanson, Brian; Steil, Lucien; Prince of Wales's Urban Design Task Force; Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, 1998</ref>\n\nA Berlin lawyer and real estate entrepreneur, Michael Sch\u00f6ne, who bought and renovated old buildings, was troubled by the wasteland of the site, believing that Potsdam would never work until its core was restored. In 1996 he initiated the first attempt at reconstruction, with the launch of a fund. The vision was that the new palace would be home to galleries, museums and cafes or upstairs apartments and offices. However, opposition from various Potsdam cliques defeated the project and the collected monies were returned to the donors.<ref name=\"Wiechers\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/1110615/|title=Stadtschloss-Vork\u00e4mpfer Michael Sch\u00f6ne blickt zur\u00fcck: Zwei Jahrzehnte f\u00fcr Knobelsdorff|last=Wiechers|first=Katharina|date=2016-09-07|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly afterwards the PDS politician Birgit M\u00fcller, then chairman of the City Council, agreed to support the reconstruction of the main portal of the Palace, the Fortuna Gate. It was a small window in time, as the PDS would soon officially oppose reconstruction. The SPD under Matthias Platzeck also supported Sch\u00f6ne.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/> In 1996 the City Castle Association was established, with Sch\u00f6ne as chairman. Large donations by the television presenter [[G\u00fcnther Jauch]] and the Federal Association of the German Cement Industry, led by J\u00fcrgen Lose, made the rebuilding of the Fortuna Gate possible.<ref name=\"Landtag\" /> It was completed in October 2002. The structure was seen as the bait to encourage rebuilding of the Palace itself, which was still opposed to by the political Left.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/print-welt/article544337/Beton-Spende-macht-Portal-moeglich.html|title=Beton-Spende macht Portal m\u00f6glich|last=Karutz|first=Hans-R\u00fcdiger|date=2000-04-14|newspaper=Welt Online|access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref>\n\nIn a dramatic night vote, in 2000 the Potsdam City Council voted for reconstruction, but this had real no support at the state level, and at the time there was a recession. When the economy improved, in May 2005 there was agreement that the parliament would relocate from its GDR building to a new parliament building in the external forms of the historic palace. Despite this, the reconstruction still had strong opponents. Rainer Speer of the SPD, then finance minister, repeatedly tried to stop the project.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/>\n\nIn 2007 a referendum was held to decide three building options for the remainder of the site. The Left Party was stunned when almost 50 percent of voters turned out (far more than for elections for the European parliament), and voted decisively for reconstruction of the Palace. \"It's not what we wanted\", the Left Party's parliamentary leader Hans-J\u00fcrgen Scharfenberg stated following the vote, \"But we'll respect people's decisions\".<ref name=\"dw.com\"/>\n\n[[Image:14-01-27-landtag-brandenburg-RalfR-158.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\nAn architectural competition was launched. The initial plan was for only the principal northern facade to be an historical reconstruction, with the wings and interior modern, and the City Palace Association feared \"cost optimised architecture\" would dispense with many of the historical elements. Two days before the final meeting of the jury competition, the Prime Minister received a call from software mogul [[Hasso Plattner]] offering a donation of \u20ac20 million to enable the entire historic facade to be reconstructed \u2013 at the time, the largest donation ever gifted in Germany by an individual.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/> Plattner later provided a further large donation to enable the roof to be clad in the original copper.<ref name=\"Landtag\" /> The Palace was completed in late 2013. The interior, which is modern, houses the [[Landtag of Brandenburg|parliament]] of the federal state of [[Brandenburg]].<ref>http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/804384/</ref>\n\nOn one of the walls of the Palace there is an inscription \"Ceci n'est pas un ch\u00e2teau\" (\"This is not a palace\"), an allusion to [[Ren\u00e9 Magritte]]'s painting ''[[The Treachery of Images]]'' - \"Ceci n'est pas une pipe\".\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=175px>\nFile:Stadtschloss Potsdam Gem\u00e4lde.jpg|The Potsdam City Palace in 1773\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-236, Potsdam, Stadtschloss.jpg|The Potsdam City Palace in 1928\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-237, Potsdam, Stadtschloss vom Turm der Nikolaikirche.jpg|The Palace prior to destruction\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-382, Potsdam, Ruinen.jpg|In ruins after World War II\nFile:Filmmuseum Potsdam mit dem L\u00f6wen der Bank von England.jpg|The remaining stables in 2005\nFile:Potsdam Alter Markt Stadtschloss.jpg|View over the empty Old Market in 2007 with the reconstructed Fortuna Gate\nFile:Potsdam Stadtschloss Baustelle 2010.JPG|Construction site in 2010\nFile:LandtagSchuschkeSeptember2012.JPG|Construction site in 2012\nFile:Stadtschloss Potsdam.jpg|The reconstructed palace in 2016\nFile:Tea Room , Stadtschloss, Potsdam.jpg|Tea Room, Stadtschloss, Potsdam, 1930\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Baroque residences]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Stadtschloss Potsdam}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h28EVb6Io6Q 'Das Potsdamer Stadtschloss in Gefahr'] (1949), historical short movie about Potsdam city palace warning against its demolition.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\u2022 Sch\u00f6ne, Michael ''Stadt sucht Mitte'', Strauss Edition, 2016\n\n{{Prussian royal residences |state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|52|23|41|N|13|03|38|E|region:DE-BB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1669]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1752]]\n[[Category:Royal residences in Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Palaces in Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in Germany]]\n[[Category:Baroque architecture in Potsdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Potsdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Germany destroyed during World War II]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildings and structures in Germany]]\n[[Category:1669 establishments in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:German Landtag buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = Potsdam City Palace\n| native_name          = Potsdamer Stadtschloss\n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      = \n| image                = Potsdam Stadtschloss 07-2017.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Main facade of the Potsdam City Palace in 2017\n| map_type             = Germany\n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = Location in Germany\n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = [[Palace]]\n| architectural_style  = [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]], [[Rococo]]\n| structural_system    = \n| cost                 =  \n| client               = [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg]]<br>[[Frederick II of Prussia]] <br> State of Brandenburg\n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| location             = \n| address              = \n| location_town        = [[Potsdam]]\n| location_country     = [[Germany]]\n| coordinates          = {{coord|52.394|13.060|display=inline}}\n| start_date           = 1662\n| completion_date      = 1669\n| inauguration_date    = \n| renovation_date      = 1744-52, 2006-13 (rebuild)\n| height               = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] \n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| awards               =\n| url                  = \n| references           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Potsdam City Palace''' ({{lang-de|Potsdamer Stadtschloss}}) is a building in [[Potsdam]], [[Germany]], located on the [[Old Market Square, Potsdam | Old Market Square]], next to the [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]] (''Nikolaikirche''). It was the second [[official residence]] (the winter residence) of the [[Rulers of Brandenburg|margraves and electors of Brandenburg]], later [[King in Prussia|kings in Prussia]], [[List of rulers of Prussia|kings of Prussia]] and [[List of German monarchs|German emperors]]. \n\nHeavily damaged in [[World War II]] and later dismantled by the [[East Germany | East German]] communist regime, the partial reconstruction, with historic facades and a modern interior, was completed in late 2013. The building has since served to house the [[Landtag of Brandenburg|parliament of the federal state of Brandenburg]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] palace was constructed on the site of an earlier fortification from 1662 to 1669 under [[Prince-Elector]] [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Friedrich Wilhelm]], and was rebuilt from 1744 to 1752 by [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] under [[Frederick II of Prussia|Friedrich II]], who performed additional interior decoration. It stood as one of the most important examples of [[Frederician Rococo]].\n\nDuring an Allied bombing attack on 14 April 1945 the City Palace was bombed and burned out, although 83 per cent of the building structure survived.<ref name=\"dw.com\">{{Cite web|title = In Surprise Vote, Potsdam Decides to Rebuild Baroque Palace {{!}} Culture {{!}} DW.COM {{!}} 05.01.2007|url = http://www.dw.com/en/in-surprise-vote-potsdam-decides-to-rebuild-baroque-palace/a-2301379|website = DW.COM|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>  However, the ruling communist party (official name: [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany]], SED) demolished the ruin in 1960 for ideological reasons.{{citation needed|reason=What ideological reasons?|date=June 2016}} The formerly cohesive Old Market lost its face. The only portion of the palace left standing was the stables, which today houses the Potsdam Museum of Film.\n\nIn 1991 construction of a modern theatre, which had been initially planned under the GDR, began on the site of the City Palace. However, the project stalled. Although some steel framework was erected, it was subsequently torn down.\n\n==Reconstruction==\nAfter the fall of the Berlin Wall, the ruling Left Party (the successor to the communists) twice rejected initiatives to reconstruct the Palace. However, in 1996 strong encouragement was provided by the \"Potsdam Project\" run by the Summer Academy for Young Architects of the [[Prince of Wales]]'s London Institute of Architecture.<ref name=\"Landtag\">\"Brief history of the new Landtag building: The long road from city palace to Landtag palace\", Landtag Brandenburg, 2014. http://www.landtag.brandenburg.de/media_fast/5701/Schriftenreihe_1_2014_englisch.pdf</ref> The Project recommended reinstatement of the historical footprint of the Palace via a partial reconstruction.<ref>''The Potsdam project, 1996'', HRH The Prince of Wales, Charles; Hanson, Brian; Steil, Lucien; Prince of Wales's Urban Design Task Force; Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, 1998</ref>\n\nA Berlin lawyer and real estate entrepreneur, Michael Sch\u00f6ne, who bought and renovated old buildings, was troubled by the wasteland of the site, believing that Potsdam would never work until its core was restored. In 1996 he initiated the first attempt at reconstruction, with the launch of a fund. The vision was that the new palace would be home to galleries, museums and cafes or upstairs apartments and offices. However, opposition from various Potsdam cliques defeated the project and the collected monies were returned to the donors.<ref name=\"Wiechers\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/1110615/|title=Stadtschloss-Vork\u00e4mpfer Michael Sch\u00f6ne blickt zur\u00fcck: Zwei Jahrzehnte f\u00fcr Knobelsdorff|last=Wiechers|first=Katharina|date=2016-09-07|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly afterwards the PDS politician Birgit M\u00fcller, then chairman of the City Council, agreed to support the reconstruction of the main portal of the Palace, the Fortuna Gate. It was a small window in time, as the PDS would soon officially oppose reconstruction. The SPD under Matthias Platzeck also supported Sch\u00f6ne.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/> In 1996 the City Castle Association was established, with Sch\u00f6ne as chairman. Large donations by the television presenter [[G\u00fcnther Jauch]] and the Federal Association of the German Cement Industry, led by J\u00fcrgen Lose, made the rebuilding of the Fortuna Gate possible.<ref name=\"Landtag\" /> It was completed in October 2002. The structure was seen as the bait to encourage rebuilding of the Palace itself, which was still opposed to by the political Left.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/print-welt/article544337/Beton-Spende-macht-Portal-moeglich.html|title=Beton-Spende macht Portal m\u00f6glich|last=Karutz|first=Hans-R\u00fcdiger|date=2000-04-14|newspaper=Welt Online|access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref>\n\nIn a dramatic night vote, in 2000 the Potsdam City Council voted for reconstruction, but this had real no support at the state level, and at the time there was a recession. When the economy improved, in May 2005 there was agreement that the parliament would relocate from its GDR building to a new parliament building in the external forms of the historic palace. Despite this, the reconstruction still had strong opponents. Rainer Speer of the SPD, then finance minister, repeatedly tried to stop the project.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/>\n\nIn 2007 a referendum was held to decide three building options for the remainder of the site. The Left Party was stunned when almost 50 percent of voters turned out (far more than for elections for the European parliament), and voted decisively for reconstruction of the Palace. \"It's not what we wanted\", the Left Party's parliamentary leader Hans-J\u00fcrgen Scharfenberg stated following the vote, \"But we'll respect people's decisions\".<ref name=\"dw.com\"/>\n\n[[Image:14-01-27-landtag-brandenburg-RalfR-158.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\nAn architectural competition was launched. The initial plan was for only the principal northern facade to be an historical reconstruction, with the wings and interior modern, and the City Palace Association feared \"cost optimised architecture\" would dispense with many of the historical elements. Two days before the final meeting of the jury competition, the Prime Minister received a call from software mogul [[Hasso Plattner]] offering a donation of \u20ac20 million to enable the entire historic facade to be reconstructed \u2013 at the time, the largest donation ever gifted in Germany by an individual.<ref name=\"Wiechers\"/> Plattner later provided a further large donation to enable the roof to be clad in the original copper.<ref name=\"Landtag\" /> The Palace was completed in late 2013. The interior, which is modern, houses the [[Landtag of Brandenburg|parliament]] of the federal state of [[Brandenburg]].<ref>http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/804384/</ref>\n\nOn one of the walls of the Palace there is an inscription \"Ceci n'est pas un ch\u00e2teau\" (\"This is not a palace\"), an allusion to [[Ren\u00e9 Magritte]]'s painting ''[[The Treachery of Images]]'' - \"Ceci n'est pas une pipe\".\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=175px>\nFile:Stadtschloss Potsdam Gem\u00e4lde.jpg|The Potsdam City Palace in 1773\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-236, Potsdam, Stadtschloss.jpg|The Potsdam City Palace in 1928\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-237, Potsdam, Stadtschloss vom Turm der Nikolaikirche.jpg|The Palace prior to destruction\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-382, Potsdam, Ruinen.jpg|In ruins after World War II\nFile:Filmmuseum Potsdam mit dem L\u00f6wen der Bank von England.jpg|The remaining stables in 2005\nFile:Potsdam Alter Markt Stadtschloss.jpg|View over the empty Old Market in 2007 with the reconstructed Fortuna Gate\nFile:Potsdam Stadtschloss Baustelle 2010.JPG|Construction site in 2010\nFile:LandtagSchuschkeSeptember2012.JPG|Construction site in 2012\nFile:Stadtschloss Potsdam.jpg|The reconstructed palace in 2016\nFile:Tea Room , Stadtschloss, Potsdam.jpg|Tea Room, Stadtschloss, Potsdam, 1930\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Baroque residences]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Stadtschloss Potsdam}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h28EVb6Io6Q 'Das Potsdamer Stadtschloss in Gefahr'] (1949), historical short movie about Potsdam city palace warning against its demolition.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\u2022 Sch\u00f6ne, Michael ''Stadt sucht Mitte'', Strauss Edition, 2016\n\n{{Prussian royal residences |state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|52|23|41|N|13|03|38|E|region:DE-BB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1669]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1752]]\n[[Category:Royal residences in Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Palaces in Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in Germany]]\n[[Category:Baroque architecture in Potsdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Potsdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Germany destroyed during World War II]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildings and structures in Germany]]\n[[Category:1669 establishments in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:German Landtag buildings]]\n", "name_user": "121.167.23.173", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_Palace,_Potsdam"}
{"title_page": "Bahrain 10\u20130 Indonesia", "text_new": "{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2014 FIFA World Cup qualification<br/><small>([[Asian Football Confederation|Asian zone]])</small><br/>Group E\n| image                   = \n| event                   = \n| team1                   = [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|BHR|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 10\n| team2                   = [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|IDN|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 0\n| details                 = [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] advances to the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Fourth Round|fourth round]] of the AFC qualification tournament <br> Bahrain eliminated from World Cup contention\n| date                    = 29 February 2012\n| stadium                 = [[Bahrain National Stadium]]\n| city                    = [[Riffa]], [[Bahrain]]\n| referee                 = [[Andre El Haddad]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n| attendance              = 3,000\n| weather                 = Clear<br />{{convert|26|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}<ref>{{cite web|title=History for Manama, Bahrain|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/OBBI/2012/2/29/DailyHistory.html?req_city=NA&req_state=NA&req_statename=NA|publisher=wunderground.com|date=2012-02-29|accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n}}\n\nOn 29 February 2012, the [[Bahrain national football team|Bahraini]] and [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] national [[association football]] teams faced each other in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying match]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. The match was played at the [[Bahrain National Stadium]] in [[Riffa]], [[Bahrain]]. This match is known for the investigation called for by [[FIFA]] afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/9116168/Bahrains-10-0-Asian-zone-World-Cup-win-over-Indonesia-prompts-Fifa-match-fixing-investigation.html|title=Bahrain's 10-0 Asian zone World Cup win over Indonesia prompts Fifa match-fixing investigation|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore this match Bahrain needed to score nine goals in order to pass [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] and to move on to the next round in qualifying. They also needed Qatar to lose their next match against [[Iran national football team|Iran]] but due to an 83rd-minute equalizer the game finished 2\u20132 and thus Qatar progressed instead of Bahrain.<ref name=telegraph9117977>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/9117977/Fifa-security-launches-investigation-into-Bahrains-unusual-10-0-victory-over-Indonesia.html|title=Fifa security launches investigation into Bahrain's 'unusual' 10\u20130 victory over Indonesia|work=The Telegraph|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPrior to the final matchday the table was:\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|show_positions=n\n\n|team1=IRN|name_IRN={{fb|IRN}}\n|team2=QAT|name_QAT={{fb|QAT}}\n|team3=BHR|name_BHR={{fb|BHR}}\n|team4=IDN|name_IDN={{fb|IDN}}\n|win_IRN=3|draw_IRN=2|loss_IRN=0|gf_IRN=15|ga_IRN=3\n|win_QAT=2|draw_QAT=3|loss_QAT=0|gf_QAT=8|ga_QAT=3\n|win_BHR=1|draw_BHR=3|loss_BHR=1|gf_BHR=3|ga_BHR=7\n|win_IDN=0|draw_IDN=0|loss_IDN=5|gf_IDN=3|ga_IDN=16\n\n|split2=y\n\n|col_Q=#ccffcc|text_Q=\n|result1=Q\n|col_R=#ffcccc|text_R=\n|result4=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\nBefore the game, [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] required a winning margin of nine goals to stand any chance of progressing to the next stage.<ref name=mail2108614>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2108614/FIFA-launch-investigation-Bahrain-10-0-win-Indonesia.html|title=FIFA launch investigation as Taylor's Bahrain win crucial World Cup qualifier 10\u20130|work=The Daily Mail|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the game, [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] had lost all five matches to date in their qualification group, allowing 16 goals in the process.<ref name=telegraph9117977/> Internal conflict in the [[Football Association of Indonesia]] lead them to prevent all [[Indonesia Super League]] players from playing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/wire-news/indonesia-fa-confidentavoiding-fifa-ban_682641.html|title=Indonesia FA confident of avoiding FIFA ban|work=Reuters|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref> They only sent players who play in the [[Indonesian Premier League]], although Indonesia's regular, better, and more experienced national players play in the [[Indonesia Super League]]. Indonesia was understood to have fielded inexperienced players due to this situation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jurejko|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17220640|title=Peter Taylor's Bahrain face Fifa investigation after 10\u20130 win|work=BBC Sport|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrior to this match, Indonesia's record loss was 9\u20130, recorded in 1974 at the hands of [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=jg501839>{{cite news|last1=Satwiko |first1=Wimbo |last2=Rahman |first2=Anita |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/sports/football-blame-game-starts-after-indonesias-10-0-loss/501839 |title=Football: Blame Game Starts After Indonesia's 10\u20130 Loss |work=Jakarta Globe |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404163909/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/sports/football-blame-game-starts-after-indonesias-10-0-loss/501839 |archivedate=4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn the six previous meetings between the two teams, each team had won twice, with two matches having been drawn.<ref name=jg501839/> The last match between the two teams was in the same qualification, which resulted a win for Bahrain 2\u20130 in Jakarta, Indonesia on 6 September 2011.\n\n==Match summary==\nIndonesia started the game with an inexperienced side, with no player holding more than 12 international [[Cap (sport)|caps]].<ref name=dtaus>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/soccer/bahrain-coach-says-his-team-did-nothing-wrong-in-10-0-world-cup-qualifying-drubbing-of-weakened-indonesia/story-e6frey4r-1226322523205|title=Bahrain coach says his team did 'nothing wrong' in 10\u20130 World Cup qualifying drubbing of weakened Indonesia|work=The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|date=10 April 2012|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> This was also the international debut for eight players in the Indonesia starting line up (except [[Syamsidar]], [[Irfan Bachdim]], and [[Ferdinand Sinaga]]).\n\n[[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] suffered an early setback when their [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] Syamsidar was shown the [[Misconduct (association football)|red card]] in the first three minutes.<ref name=mail2108614/> After Bahrain scored the resultant penalty, they went on to be awarded a total of four penalties in the match, including three in the first half, although substitute Indonesia goalkeeper [[Andi Muhammad Guntur]] managed to save two of the four kicks.<ref name=jg501839/>\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date=29 February 2012\n|time=16:30 [[Arabia Standard Time|AST]]\n|team1=[[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] {{flagicon|BHR}}\n|score=10\u20130\n|report=[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/round=257791/match=300172578/report.html Report]\n|team2={{flagicon|INA}} [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]]\n|goals1=[[Ismail Abdul-Latif|Latif]] {{goal|5|pen.|71||75}}<br />[[Mohammed Tayeb Al Alawi|Al Alawi]] {{goal|16||61}}<br />[[Mahmood Abdulrahman|Abdulrahman]] {{goal|35|pen.|42}}<br />[[Sayed Saeed|Dhiya]] {{goal|63||82||90+4}}\n|stadium=[[Bahrain National Stadium]], [[Manama]]\n|attendance=3,000\n|referee=[[Andre El Haddad]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n}}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''BAHRAIN:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Sayed Mohammed Jaffer|Sayed Jaffer]]\n|-\n| ||'''2''' ||[[Waleed Al Hayam]]\n|-\n| ||'''3'''||[[Abdulla Marzooqi|Abdulla Marzooq]]\n|-\n| ||'''4''' ||[[Sayed Saeed|Sayed Dhiya]]\n|-\n| ||'''5'''||[[Saleh Abdulhameed]]\n|-\n| ||'''7'''||[[Ali Abdulwahab]]\n|-\n| ||'''10''' ||[[Mohammed Tayeb Al Alawi]]\n|-\n| ||'''11''' ||[[Ismail Abdul-Latif]]\n|-\n| ||'''13''' ||[[Mahmood Abdulrahman]] || || {{suboff|90+2}}\n|-\n| ||'''14'''||[[Salman Isa]]\n|-\n| ||'''15'''||[[Abdullah Omar]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n| ||'''6'''||[[Dawood Saad]]\n|-\n| ||'''8''' ||[[Hassan Jameel (footballer)|Hassan Jameel]]\n|-\n| ||'''9'''||[[Hamad Al Bannki]]\n|-\n| ||'''12'''||[[Ali Norooz Hasan]]\n|-\n| ||'''16'''||[[Isa Moosa]]\n|-\n| ||'''17'''||[[Mohamed Duaij]]\n|-\n| ||'''18''' ||[[Fahad Hasan]] || || {{subon|90+2}}\n|-\n| ||'''19''' ||[[Ahmed Mubarak Al Khattal]]\n|-\n| ||'''20''' ||[[Sami Mohammed]]\n|-\n| ||'''21''' ||[[Hamad Ebrahim]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''22''' ||[[Abbas Ahmed Khamis]]\n|-\n| ||'''23''' ||[[Ebrahim Al Obaildi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''INDONESIA:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Syamsidar]] || {{sent off|0|3}}\n|-\n|LM ||'''6'''||[[Rendy Irawan]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[Muhammad Taufiq]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''10'''||[[Irfan Bachdim]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''11''' ||[[Aditya Putra Dewa]] || || {{suboff|61}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''13'''||[[Gunawan Dwi Cahyo|Gunawan Cahyo]] || || {{suboff|68}}\n|-\n|RB ||'''14'''||[[Hengky Ardiles]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''15'''||[[Diego Michiels]] || {{yel|30}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''17'''||[[Ferdinand Sinaga]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''19'''||[[Slamet Nurcahyo]] || || {{suboff|4}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''22'''||[[Abdul Rahman (Indonesian footballer)|Abdul Rahman]] || {{yel|84}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||[[Sigit Meiko Susanto]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' ||[[Ricky Ohorella]] || || {{subon|61}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||[[Samsul Arif]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''12''' ||[[Andi Muhammad Guntur]] || || {{subon|4}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''16''' ||[[Rasul Zainuddin]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21''' ||[[Abdul Abanda Rahman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23''' ||[[Wahyu Wijiastanto]] || || {{subon|68}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|INA}} [[Aji Santoso]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Ziad Birak ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n<br />Hadi El Kassar ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />[[Radwan Ghandour]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n|}\n\n==Post match==\nThe final table was as follows:\n{{:2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|transcludesection=Group E|show_matches=n}}\nFollowing the match, Indonesia finished the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|third round]] with the worst overall record of the 20 competing teams, having scored no points at all in the round while conceding a total of 26 goals.<ref name=jg501839/>\n\nBahrain also failed to qualify for the next stage of qualifying, finishing with two wins, three draws and a single loss.<ref name=dtaus/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/round=257791/match=300172578/report.html Official match report at FIFA.com]\n\n{{FIFA World Cup 2014 Qualifiers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bahrain 10-0 Indonesia}}\n[[Category:2012 in Asian football]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification matches]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)]]\n[[Category:Bahrain national football team matches]]\n[[Category:Indonesia national football team matches]]\n[[Category:2011\u201312 in Bahraini football]]\n[[Category:2011\u201312 in Indonesian football]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup controversies]]\n[[Category:February 2012 sports events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2014 FIFA World Cup qualification<br/><small>([[Asian Football Confederation|Asian zone]])</small><br/>Group E\n| image                   = \n| event                   = \n| team1                   = [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|BHR|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 10\n| team2                   = [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|IDN|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 0\n| details                 = [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] advances to the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Fourth Round|fourth round]] of the AFC qualification tournament <br> Bahrain eliminated from World Cup contention\n| date                    = 29 February 2012\n| stadium                 = [[Bahrain National Stadium]]\n| city                    = [[Riffa]], [[Bahrain]]\n| referee                 = [[Andre El Haddad]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n| attendance              = 3,000\n| weather                 = Clear<br />{{convert|26|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}<ref>{{cite web|title=History for Manama, Bahrain|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/OBBI/2012/2/29/DailyHistory.html?req_city=NA&req_state=NA&req_statename=NA|publisher=wunderground.com|date=2012-02-29|accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n}}\n\nOn 29 February 2012, the [[Bahrain national football team|Bahraini]] and [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] national [[association football]] teams faced each other in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying match]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. The match was played at the [[Bahrain National Stadium]] in [[Riffa]], [[Bahrain]]. This match is known for the investigation called for by [[FIFA]] afterwards.{{Clarify|date=September 2015}}\n\nBefore this match Bahrain needed to score nine goals in order to pass [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] and to move on to the next round in qualifying. They also needed Qatar to lose their next match against [[Iran national football team|Iran]] but due to an 83rd-minute equalizer the game finished 2\u20132 and thus Qatar progressed instead of Bahrain.<ref name=telegraph9117977>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/9117977/Fifa-security-launches-investigation-into-Bahrains-unusual-10-0-victory-over-Indonesia.html|title=Fifa security launches investigation into Bahrain's 'unusual' 10\u20130 victory over Indonesia|work=The Telegraph|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPrior to the final matchday the table was:\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|show_positions=n\n\n|team1=IRN|name_IRN={{fb|IRN}}\n|team2=QAT|name_QAT={{fb|QAT}}\n|team3=BHR|name_BHR={{fb|BHR}}\n|team4=IDN|name_IDN={{fb|IDN}}\n|win_IRN=3|draw_IRN=2|loss_IRN=0|gf_IRN=15|ga_IRN=3\n|win_QAT=2|draw_QAT=3|loss_QAT=0|gf_QAT=8|ga_QAT=3\n|win_BHR=1|draw_BHR=3|loss_BHR=1|gf_BHR=3|ga_BHR=7\n|win_IDN=0|draw_IDN=0|loss_IDN=5|gf_IDN=3|ga_IDN=16\n\n|split2=y\n\n|col_Q=#ccffcc|text_Q=\n|result1=Q\n|col_R=#ffcccc|text_R=\n|result4=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\nBefore the game, [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] required a winning margin of nine goals to stand any chance of progressing to the next stage.<ref name=mail2108614>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2108614/FIFA-launch-investigation-Bahrain-10-0-win-Indonesia.html|title=FIFA launch investigation as Taylor's Bahrain win crucial World Cup qualifier 10\u20130|work=The Daily Mail|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the game, [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] had lost all five matches to date in their qualification group, allowing 16 goals in the process.<ref name=telegraph9117977/> Internal conflict in the [[Football Association of Indonesia]] lead them to prevent all [[Indonesia Super League]] players from playing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/wire-news/indonesia-fa-confidentavoiding-fifa-ban_682641.html|title=Indonesia FA confident of avoiding FIFA ban|work=Reuters|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref> They only sent players who play in the [[Indonesian Premier League]], although Indonesia's regular, better, and more experienced national players play in the [[Indonesia Super League]]. Indonesia was understood to have fielded inexperienced players due to this situation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jurejko|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17220640|title=Peter Taylor's Bahrain face Fifa investigation after 10\u20130 win|work=BBC Sport|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrior to this match, Indonesia's record loss was 9\u20130, recorded in 1974 at the hands of [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=jg501839>{{cite news|last1=Satwiko |first1=Wimbo |last2=Rahman |first2=Anita |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/sports/football-blame-game-starts-after-indonesias-10-0-loss/501839 |title=Football: Blame Game Starts After Indonesia's 10\u20130 Loss |work=Jakarta Globe |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404163909/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/sports/football-blame-game-starts-after-indonesias-10-0-loss/501839 |archivedate=4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn the six previous meetings between the two teams, each team had won twice, with two matches having been drawn.<ref name=jg501839/>\n\n==Match summary==\nIndonesia started the game with an inexperienced side, with no player holding more than 12 international [[Cap (sport)|caps]].<ref name=dtaus>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/soccer/bahrain-coach-says-his-team-did-nothing-wrong-in-10-0-world-cup-qualifying-drubbing-of-weakened-indonesia/story-e6frey4r-1226322523205|title=Bahrain coach says his team did 'nothing wrong' in 10\u20130 World Cup qualifying drubbing of weakened Indonesia|work=The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|date=10 April 2012|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> This was also the international debut for eight players in the Indonesia starting line up (except [[Syamsidar]], [[Irfan Bachdim]], and [[Ferdinand Sinaga]]).\n\n[[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] suffered an early setback when their [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] Syamsidar was shown the [[Misconduct (association football)|red card]] in the first three minutes.<ref name=mail2108614/> After Bahrain scored the resultant penalty, they went on to be awarded a total of four penalties in the match, including three in the first half, although substitute Indonesia goalkeeper [[Andi Muhammad Guntur]] managed to save two of the four kicks.<ref name=jg501839/>\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date=29 February 2012\n|time=16:30 [[Arabia Standard Time|AST]]\n|team1=[[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] {{flagicon|BHR}}\n|score=10\u20130\n|report=[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/round=257791/match=300172578/report.html Report]\n|team2={{flagicon|INA}} [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]]\n|goals1=[[Ismail Abdul-Latif|Latif]] {{goal|5|pen.|71||75}}<br />[[Mohammed Tayeb Al Alawi|Al Alawi]] {{goal|16||61}}<br />[[Mahmood Abdulrahman|Abdulrahman]] {{goal|35|pen.|42}}<br />[[Sayed Saeed|Dhiya]] {{goal|63||82||90+4}}\n|stadium=[[Bahrain National Stadium]], [[Manama]]\n|attendance=3,000\n|referee=[[Andre El Haddad]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n}}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''BAHRAIN:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Sayed Mohammed Jaffer|Sayed Jaffer]]\n|-\n| ||'''2''' ||[[Waleed Al Hayam]]\n|-\n| ||'''3'''||[[Abdulla Marzooqi|Abdulla Marzooq]]\n|-\n| ||'''4''' ||[[Sayed Saeed|Sayed Dhiya]]\n|-\n| ||'''5'''||[[Saleh Abdulhameed]]\n|-\n| ||'''7'''||[[Ali Abdulwahab]]\n|-\n| ||'''10''' ||[[Mohammed Tayeb Al Alawi]]\n|-\n| ||'''11''' ||[[Ismail Abdul-Latif]]\n|-\n| ||'''13''' ||[[Mahmood Abdulrahman]] || || {{suboff|90+2}}\n|-\n| ||'''14'''||[[Salman Isa]]\n|-\n| ||'''15'''||[[Abdullah Omar]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n| ||'''6'''||[[Dawood Saad]]\n|-\n| ||'''8''' ||[[Hassan Jameel (footballer)|Hassan Jameel]]\n|-\n| ||'''9'''||[[Hamad Al Bannki]]\n|-\n| ||'''12'''||[[Ali Norooz Hasan]]\n|-\n| ||'''16'''||[[Isa Moosa]]\n|-\n| ||'''17'''||[[Mohamed Duaij]]\n|-\n| ||'''18''' ||[[Fahad Hasan]] || || {{subon|90+2}}\n|-\n| ||'''19''' ||[[Ahmed Mubarak Al Khattal]]\n|-\n| ||'''20''' ||[[Sami Mohammed]]\n|-\n| ||'''21''' ||[[Hamad Ebrahim]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''22''' ||[[Abbas Ahmed Khamis]]\n|-\n| ||'''23''' ||[[Ebrahim Al Obaildi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''INDONESIA:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Syamsidar]] || {{sent off|0|3}}\n|-\n|LM ||'''6'''||[[Rendy Irawan]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[Muhammad Taufiq]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''10'''||[[Irfan Bachdim]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''11''' ||[[Aditya Putra Dewa]] || || {{suboff|61}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''13'''||[[Gunawan Dwi Cahyo|Gunawan Cahyo]] || || {{suboff|68}}\n|-\n|RB ||'''14'''||[[Hengky Ardiles]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''15'''||[[Diego Michiels]] || {{yel|30}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''17'''||[[Ferdinand Sinaga]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''19'''||[[Slamet Nurcahyo]] || || {{suboff|4}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''22'''||[[Abdul Rahman (Indonesian footballer)|Abdul Rahman]] || {{yel|84}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||[[Sigit Meiko Susanto]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' ||[[Ricky Ohorella]] || || {{subon|61}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||[[Samsul Arif]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''12''' ||[[Andi Muhammad Guntur]] || || {{subon|4}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''16''' ||[[Rasul Zainuddin]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21''' ||[[Abdul Abanda Rahman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23''' ||[[Wahyu Wijiastanto]] || || {{subon|68}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|INA}} [[Aji Santoso]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Ziad Birak ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n<br />Hadi El Kassar ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />[[Radwan Ghandour]] ([[Federation Libanaise de Football|Lebanon]])\n|}\n\n==Post match==\nThe final table was as follows:\n{{:2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|transcludesection=Group E|show_matches=n}}\nFollowing the match, Indonesia finished the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|third round]] with the worst overall record of the 20 competing teams, having scored no points at all in the round while conceding a total of 26 goals.<ref name=jg501839/>\n\nBahrain also failed to qualify for the next stage of qualifying, finishing with two wins, three draws and a single loss.<ref name=dtaus/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/round=257791/match=300172578/report.html Official match report at FIFA.com]\n\n{{FIFA World Cup 2014 Qualifiers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bahrain 10-0 Indonesia}}\n[[Category:2012 in Asian football]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification matches]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)]]\n[[Category:Bahrain national football team matches]]\n[[Category:Indonesia national football team matches]]\n[[Category:2011\u201312 in Bahraini football]]\n[[Category:2011\u201312 in Indonesian football]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup controversies]]\n[[Category:February 2012 sports events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "121.167.23.173", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bahrain_10%E2%80%930_Indonesia"}
{"title_page": "Old Market Square, Potsdam", "text_new": "[[File:Alter Markt im M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|thumb|309x309px|Old Market Square (March 2016)]]\n[[File:Alter Markt Potsdam.jpg|thumb|Old Market Square (2005, before the reconstruction of the [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]])]]\n[[File:Karl Christian Wilhelm Baron, Alter Markt in Potsdam mit Stadtschloss (Blick in Richtung Schlossstra\u00dfe), GK I 5747 original.jpg|thumb|Carl Christian Wilhelm Baron \u2014 ''Alter Markt in Potsdam'' (1772)]]\nThe '''Old Market Square''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Alter Markt'') is a centrally located square in downtown [[Potsdam]] which forms the historical center of the city. The square consists of the area around [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]]. Today the term refers in particular to the area directly in front of the church. It is bordered by several prestigious historical buildings.\n\n== History ==\nThe [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]] was originally erected in 1666 under the order of [[Prince-elector|Elector]] [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Frederick William]]. At the time the spot was part of a castle grounds. The [[Old City Hall, Potsdam|Old City Hall]] was developed between 1753\u20131755 under the direction of architects [[Jan Bouman]] and [[Carl Ludwig Hildebrant]]. The marble obelisk in front of the church was added in 1753, following a design by [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]], in order to emphasize the Roman character of the square. The most famous building in the square, [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]], was erected from 1830\u20131837 as a centrally-planned building after classical-style designs by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]].\n\nThe buildings in the square were largely destroyed by [[World War II]] [[Strategic bombing during World War II|air raids]] by the [[Royal Air Force]] in [[April 1945]]. St. Nicholas' Church and the Old City Hall were immediately rebuilt after 1945, and the marble obelisk was restored in 1979. The shaft of the obelisk originally depicted rulers of the [[House of Hohenzollern]] who had heavily influenced [[Potsdam]]: [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg]], as well as the kings [[Frederick I of Prussia|Frederick I]], [[Frederick William I of Prussia|Frederick William I]], and [[Frederick the Great]]. Upon restoration the references to the old rulers were removed and replaced by portraits of popular Potsdam architects [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]], [[Carl von Gontard]], [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]], and [[Friedrich Ludwig Persius]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=F\u00fcrsten, Helden, gro\u00dfe Geister: Denkmalgeschichten aus der Mark Brandenburg|last=Caspar|first=Helmut|date=2004-01-01|publisher=bebra|isbn=9783814801339|edition=1., Aufl.|pages=77\u201378|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3814801334|country=de}}}}</ref> Other war ruins were demolished and removed, including those of the City Palace and [[Museum Barberini|Barberini Palace]]. The square was thus left open on the south side. Between 1971 and 1977, a modern-style building for the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]] was added to the west side of the square. Shortly before the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], new construction of a theater began in the former location of the City Palace. Its skeleton was torn down several years after the local government decided to bring new construction in line with the historical style. A new location for the theater (today the [[Hans Otto Theater]]) was selected on the shore of the [[Tiefer See, Potsdam|Tiefer See]] in the city. In 2007 incremental reconstruction of the entire square was resumed.<gallery>\nFile:Alter Markt Potsdam 1837.jpg|1837: View from the south  (St. Nicholas' Church does not yet have its dome)\nFile:Potsdam Alter Markt 1900.jpg|1900: From the northeast\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-002, Potsdam, Alter Markt, Fortunaportal, Palast Barberini.jpg|1928: View of the [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]] and Barberini Palace\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-373, Potsdam, Nikolaikirche.jpg|Destruction after 1945 [[Royal Air Force]] raids of [[World War II]]\nFile:Museum Barberini M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: [[Museum Barberini]] almost ready to open\nFile:Palast Pompei Potsdam G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: Pompei Palace\nFile:Noacksches Haus M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: Noacksche Haus\n</gallery>\n\nThe Potsdam capital now aims for a complete restoration of the square in its original form, along with the bordering historical area, in around 2025. The following points have been implemented so far, in the quest for a revived ''Potsdamer Mitte'' (downtown):<ref>[https://www.potsdam.de/sites/default/files/documents/2016_01_11_fabla-9_2016_v012_eng_ansicht-web.pdf Potsdam City Center]</ref>\n* The construction of the [[Landtag of Brandenburg]], whose exterior and courtyard match those of the destroyed [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]]. The elaborate Gate of Fortune (''Fortunaportal'') on the market-side entrance was rebuilt in 2002 after a donation by the journalist [[G\u00fcnther Jauch]]. The construction exactly matches its original [[Attic style]].\n* On the south side of the square is the ''Pompei Palace'', a replica of the [[Verona]] palace of the same name. This copy of a Renaissance-nobility palace was built by [[Carl Ludwig Hildebrant]] in 1754. Original [[Mascaron (architecture)|mascarons]] from the first buildings of Potsdam have been inserted into the fa\u00e7ade of the building.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Friedrich als Bauherr|last=Giersberg|first=Hans-Joachim|date=2001-01-01|publisher=Orbis|isbn=9783572012398|edition=sonderausgabe|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3572012392|country=de}}}}</ref>\n* Also to the south lies the [[Museum Barberini]], a copy of the previous building, the [[Barberini Palace, Potsdam|Barberini Palace]]. The museum was funded by the German billionaire [[Hasso Plattner]]. The former [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] building was built by [[Carl von Gontard]] in 1771\u20131772, inspired by the Roman-style Renaissance palace [[Palazzo Barberini]]. The newly built museum will open in spring 2017.\n* Both palace replicas are linked by the narrow ''Noacksche Haus'', designed by [[Carl von Gontard]] in 1777 in [[Palladian architecture|Palladian style]]. While the building is sometimes alleged to be related to the [[Palazzo Chiericati]] in [[Vicenza]], this is unverifiable and likely only a trick by the building contractors to raise the value of the condominiums within.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Potsdam, Berlin, Bayreuth: Carl Philipp Christian von Gontard (1731-1791) und seine b\u00fcrgerlichen Wohnh\u00e4user, Immediatbauten und Stadtpalais|last=Fick|first=Astrid|date=2000-01-01|publisher=M. Imhof|isbn=9783932526428|page=87|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3932526422|country=uk}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.de/Die-Palastbauten-Andrea-Palladio-HERBERT/dp/B002XF2U30|title=Die Palastbauten des Andrea Palladio.|last=P\u00e9e|first=Herbert|date=1941-01-01|publisher=W\u00fcrzburg-Aum\u00fchle, Konrad Triltsch|page=30|language=German}}</ref>\n* To the east is the Old City Hall, a copy of a fa\u00e7ade planned (but never constructed) by [[Andrea Palladio]] for the Count of Angarano in [[Vicenza]]. It was erected by [[Jan Bouman]] in 1755. Today the building hosts the Potsdam Museum, which also extends into the neighboring buildings: the so-called ''Windelbandsche'' and ''Lehmannsche Haus'' (often known since the time of the [[East Germany|DDR]] as ''Knobelsdorffhaus'', even though [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] never lived there).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Das B\u00fcrgerhaus in Potsdam - 2 B\u00e4nde|last=Mielke|first=Friedrich|date=1972-01-01|publisher=Verlag Ernst Wasmuth T\u00fcbingen|isbn=9783803000163|edition=1. Auflage|page=330|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3803000165|country=de}}}}</ref>\n* On the west side is a building erected in 1970 by the [[East Germany|East German]] government as a local [[teacher training college]]. Today it houses two departments of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]]. The reinforced concrete construction is a copy of the fa\u00e7ade of a bank building erected by [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]] in 1962. The building was planned to be torn down in 2017, according to a decision of the local Potsdam government.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Potsdam/Stadt-und-Land-einigen-sich-auf-Umzugstermin-fuer-FH-Potsdam-bis-Oktober-2017|title=Bis Oktober 2017 soll Geb\u00e4ude am Alten Markt ger\u00e4umt sein \u2013 Umzug der Fachhochschule endg\u00fcltig abgesagt|last=Bosschaart|first=Jan|website=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> It would be replaced with about 50 new housing units.\n\n== Buildings ==\nThe square is surrounded by the following buildings and facilities:\n* The evangelical [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]], a [[Classical architecture|classical]] building designed by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]]\n* The [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]], reconstructed in 2013\n* The marble obelisk in the middle of the square, redeveloped in 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/913547/|title=Knobelsdorff-Stele: Obelisk am Alten Markt fertig saniert|last=Kramer|first=Henri|date=2014-11-24|newspaper=[[Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten]]|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* The Potsdam Museum, inside both the Old City Hall building (topped by a golden statue of [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]]) and the ''Knobelsdorffhaus''\n* The Humboldt Quartier, reconstructed in 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Potsdam/Neues-Leben-an-der-Alten-Fahrt|title=Neues Leben an der Alten Fahrt|last=Kirf|first=Marcel|website=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/792600/|title=Baustart an der Alten Fahrt|last=Berg|first=Guido|date=2013-09-30|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* The original main building of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]], scheduled to be torn down in 2017<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Potsdam-stadtschloss-landtag.JPG|[[City Palace, Potsdam|Potsdam City Palace]], seat of the [[Landtag of Brandenburg]]\nFile:Potsdam - Fortunaportal 2007.jpg|The Gate of Fortune in 2007, before the rebuilding of the City Palace\nFile:Altes Rathaus und Knobelsdorffhaus - Potsdam (2014).png|Old City Hall and Knobelsdorffhaus (on right)\nFile:Potsdam Obelisk.jpg|Ornamentation of the marble obelisk (before redevelopment in 2014)\nFile:Fachhochschule am Alten Markt.jpg|The building of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]], to be cleared and torn down in 2017\n</gallery>\n\nConstruction projects at and around the Old Market Square:\n* The [[Museum Barberini]] (construction to be finished in 2016)\n* Housing and shopping areas (construction to be finished around 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/brandenburgi/neuer-landtag-mit-dem-stadtschloss-hat-potsdam-sein-herz-wieder/8915312.html|title=Neuer Landtag: Mit dem Stadtschloss hat Potsdam sein Herz wieder|last=Straube|first=Peer|website=Berliner Tagesspiegel|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* ''Steubenplatz'', with a memorial of [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben]] (in planning)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/847396/|title=Warten auf Steuben|last=Haase|first=Jana|date=2014-04-17|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* The ''Ringerkolonnade'' will be moved back from the Potsdam Lustgarten to its old position by the City Palace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/991270/|title=Historische Mitte in Potsdam: Die R\u00fcckkehr der S\u00e4ulen|last=Catenhusen|first=Holger|date=2015-07-28|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Alter Markt (Potsdam)}}\n\n* [http://www.kubische-panoramen.de/index.php?id_id=490&id_version=Quicktime 360-degree panorama from Kubische Panoramen (requires Quicktime)]\n* [http://www.panoramann.de/panos/potsdam/panorama_potsdam_p026.html 360-degree panorama from Panoramann (requires Flash)]\n\n{{coord|52|23|45|N|13|3|40|E|type:landmark_region:DE-BB|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in Germany]]\n[[Category:Squares in Potsdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Germany destroyed during World War II]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildings and structures in Germany]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Potsdam]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Alter Markt im M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|thumb|309x309px|Old Market Square (March 2016)]]\n[[File:Alter Markt Potsdam.jpg|thumb|Old Market Square (2005, before the reconstruction of the [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]])]]\n[[File:Karl Christian Wilhelm Baron, Alter Markt in Potsdam mit Stadtschloss (Blick in Richtung Schlossstra\u00dfe), GK I 5747 original.jpg|thumb|Carl Christian Wilhelm Baron \u2014 ''Alter Markt in Potsdam'' (1772)]]\nThe '''Old Market Square''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Alter Markt'') is a centrally located square in downtown [[Potsdam]] which forms the historical center of the city. The square consists of the area around [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]]. Today the term refers in particular to the area directly in front of the church. It is bordered by several prestigious historical buildings.\n\n== History ==\nThe [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]] was originally erected in 1666 under the order of [[Prince-elector|Elector]] [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Frederick William]]. At the time the spot was part of a castle grounds. The [[Old City Hall, Potsdam|Old City Hall]] was developed between 1753\u20131755 under the direction of architects [[Jan Bouman]] and [[Carl Ludwig Hildebrant]]. The marble obelisk in front of the church was added in 1753, following a design by [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]], in order to emphasize the Roman character of the square. The most famous building in the square, [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]], was erected from 1830\u20131837 as a centrally-planned building after classical-style designs by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]].\n\nThe buildings in the square were largely destroyed by [[World War II]] [[Strategic bombing during World War II|air raids]] by the [[Royal Air Force]] in [[April 1945]]. St. Nicholas' Church and the Old City Hall were immediately rebuilt after 1945, and the marble obelisk was restored in 1979. The shaft of the obelisk originally depicted rulers of the [[House of Hohenzollern]] who had heavily influenced [[Potsdam]]: [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg]], as well as the kings [[Frederick I of Prussia|Frederick I]], [[Frederick William I of Prussia|Frederick William I]], and [[Frederick the Great]]. Upon restoration the references to the old rulers were removed and replaced by portraits of popular Potsdam architects [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]], [[Carl von Gontard]], [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]], and [[Friedrich Ludwig Persius]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=F\u00fcrsten, Helden, gro\u00dfe Geister: Denkmalgeschichten aus der Mark Brandenburg|last=Caspar|first=Helmut|date=2004-01-01|publisher=bebra|isbn=9783814801339|edition=1., Aufl.|pages=77\u201378|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3814801334|country=de}}}}</ref> Other war ruins were demolished and removed, including those of the City Palace and [[Museum Barberini|Barberini Palace]]. The square was thus left open on the south side. Between 1971 and 1977, a modern-style building for the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]] was added to the west side of the square. Shortly before the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], new construction of a theater began in the former location of the City Palace. Its skeleton was torn down several years after the local government decided to bring new construction in line with the historical style. A new location for the theater (today the [[Hans Otto Theater]]) was selected on the shore of the [[Tiefer See, Potsdam|Tiefer See]] in the city. In 2007 incremental reconstruction of the entire square was resumed.<gallery>\nFile:Alter Markt Potsdam 1837.jpg|1837: View from the south  (St. Nicholas' Church does not yet have its dome)\nFile:Potsdam Alter Markt 1900.jpg|1900: From the northeast\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-002, Potsdam, Alter Markt, Fortunaportal, Palast Barberini.jpg|1928: View of the [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]] and Barberini Palace\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 170-373, Potsdam, Nikolaikirche.jpg|Destruction after 1945 [[Royal Air Force]] raids of [[World War II]]\nFile:Museum Barberini M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: [[Museum Barberini]] almost ready to open\nFile:Palast Pompei Potsdam G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: Pompei Palace\nFile:Noacksches Haus M\u00e4rz 2016 G\u00f6pel.jpg|2016: Noacksche Haus\n</gallery>\n\nThe Potsdam capital now aims for a complete restoration of the square in its original form, along with the bordering historical area, in around 2025. The following points have been implemented so far, in the quest for a revived ''Potsdamer Mitte'' (downtown):<ref>[https://www.potsdam.de/sites/default/files/documents/2016_01_11_fabla-9_2016_v012_eng_ansicht-web.pdf Potsdam City Center]</ref>\n* The construction of the [[Landtag of Brandenburg]], whose exterior and courtyard match those of the destroyed [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]]. The elaborate Gate of Fortune (''Fortunaportal'') on the market-side entrance was rebuilt in 2002 after a donation by the journalist [[G\u00fcnther Jauch]]. The construction exactly matches its original [[Attic style]].\n* On the south side of the square is the ''Pompei Palace'', a replica of the [[Verona]] palace of the same name. This copy of a Renaissance-nobility palace was built by [[Carl Ludwig Hildebrant]] in 1754. Original [[Mascaron (architecture)|mascarons]] from the first buildings of Potsdam have been inserted into the fa\u00e7ade of the building.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Friedrich als Bauherr|last=Giersberg|first=Hans-Joachim|date=2001-01-01|publisher=Orbis|isbn=9783572012398|edition=sonderausgabe|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3572012392|country=de}}}}</ref>\n* Also to the south lies the [[Museum Barberini]], a copy of the previous building, the [[Barberini Palace, Potsdam|Barberini Palace]]. The museum was funded by the German billionaire [[Hasso Plattner]]. The former [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] building was built by [[Carl von Gontard]] in 1771\u20131772, inspired by the Roman-style Renaissance palace [[Palazzo Barberini]]. The newly built museum will open in spring 2017.\n* Both palace replicas are linked by the narrow ''Noacksche Haus'', designed by [[Carl von Gontard]] in 1777 in [[Palladian architecture|Palladian style]]. While the building is sometimes alleged to be related to the [[Palazzo Chiericati]] in [[Vicenza]], this is unverifiable and likely only a trick by the building contractors to raise the value of the condominiums within.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Potsdam, Berlin, Bayreuth: Carl Philipp Christian von Gontard (1731-1791) und seine b\u00fcrgerlichen Wohnh\u00e4user, Immediatbauten und Stadtpalais|last=Fick|first=Astrid|date=2000-01-01|publisher=M. Imhof|isbn=9783932526428|page=87|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3932526422|country=uk}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.de/Die-Palastbauten-Andrea-Palladio-HERBERT/dp/B002XF2U30|title=Die Palastbauten des Andrea Palladio.|last=P\u00e9e|first=Herbert|date=1941-01-01|publisher=W\u00fcrzburg-Aum\u00fchle, Konrad Triltsch|page=30|language=German}}</ref>\n* To the east is the Old City Hall, a copy of a fa\u00e7ade planned (but never constructed) by [[Andrea Palladio]] for the Count of Angarano in [[Vicenza]]. It was erected by [[Jan Bouman]] in 1755. Today the building hosts the Potsdam Museum, which also extends into the neighboring buildings: the so-called ''Windelbandsche'' and ''Lehmannsche Haus'' (often known since the time of the [[East Germany|DDR]] as ''Knobelsdorffhaus'', even though [[Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff]] never lived there).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Das B\u00fcrgerhaus in Potsdam - 2 B\u00e4nde|last=Mielke|first=Friedrich|date=1972-01-01|publisher=Verlag Ernst Wasmuth T\u00fcbingen|isbn=9783803000163|edition=1. Auflage|page=330|language=German|id= {{ASIN|3803000165|country=de}}}}</ref>\n* On the west side is a building erected in 1970 by the [[East Germany|East German]] government as a local [[teacher training college]]. Today it houses two departments of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]]. The reinforced concrete construction is a copy of the fa\u00e7ade of a bank building erected by [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]] in 1962. The current building will be torn down in 2017, according to a decision of the local Potsdam government.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Potsdam/Stadt-und-Land-einigen-sich-auf-Umzugstermin-fuer-FH-Potsdam-bis-Oktober-2017|title=Bis Oktober 2017 soll Geb\u00e4ude am Alten Markt ger\u00e4umt sein \u2013 Umzug der Fachhochschule endg\u00fcltig abgesagt|last=Bosschaart|first=Jan|website=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> It will be replaced with about 50 new housing units.\n\n== Buildings ==\nThe square is surrounded by the following buildings and facilities:\n* The evangelical [[St. Nicholas' Church, Potsdam|St. Nicholas' Church]], a [[Classical architecture|classical]] building designed by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]]\n* The [[City Palace, Potsdam|City Palace]], reconstructed in 2013\n* The marble obelisk in the middle of the square, redeveloped in 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/913547/|title=Knobelsdorff-Stele: Obelisk am Alten Markt fertig saniert|last=Kramer|first=Henri|date=2014-11-24|newspaper=[[Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten]]|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* The Potsdam Museum, inside both the Old City Hall building (topped by a golden statue of [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]]) and the ''Knobelsdorffhaus''\n* The Humboldt Quartier, reconstructed in 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Potsdam/Neues-Leben-an-der-Alten-Fahrt|title=Neues Leben an der Alten Fahrt|last=Kirf|first=Marcel|website=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pnn.de/potsdam/792600/|title=Baustart an der Alten Fahrt|last=Berg|first=Guido|date=2013-09-30|newspaper=Potsdamer Neueste Nachrichten|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* The original main building of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]], scheduled to be torn down in 2017<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Potsdam-stadtschloss-landtag.JPG|[[City Palace, Potsdam|Potsdam City Palace]], seat of the [[Landtag of Brandenburg]]\nFile:Potsdam - Fortunaportal 2007.jpg|The Gate of Fortune in 2007, before the rebuilding of the City Palace\nFile:Altes Rathaus und Knobelsdorffhaus - Potsdam (2014).png|Old City Hall and Knobelsdorffhaus (on right)\nFile:Potsdam Obelisk.jpg|Ornamentation of the marble obelisk (before redevelopment in 2014)\nFile:Fachhochschule am Alten Markt.jpg|The building of the [[Fachhochschule Potsdam]], to be cleared and torn down in 2017\n</gallery>\n\nConstruction projects at and around the Old Market Square:\n* The [[Museum Barberini]] (construction to be finished in 2016)\n* Housing and shopping areas (construction to be finished around 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/brandenburgi/neuer-landtag-mit-dem-stadtschloss-hat-potsdam-sein-herz-wieder/8915312.html|title=Neuer Landtag: Mit dem Stadtschloss hat Potsdam sein Herz wieder|last=Straube|first=Peer|website=Berliner Tagesspiegel|language=German|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n* ''Steubenplatz'', with a memorial of [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben]] (in planning)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http: